IMHO, the particle fix feels wrong. Apparently the particles always have the same size (like "4x4 px" or whatever), regardless of resolution.
I would expect the particle to scale with the resolution (like it does in the GL renderers)
d_pix_shift = 8 - (int)((float)r_refdef.vrect.width / 320.0 + 0.5); means that at 320x240, d_pix_shift will be 7.
So at 640x480 it should be 6 and at 1280x960 it should be 5.
The following code should yield that behavior and seems to work.
It's a matter of taste whether we should round up (+0.5 in last line) or not; it makes particles in resolutions between320 and 640 or 640 and 1280 look a bit bigger than they should.
	float widthFac = (float)r_refdef.vrect.width / 320.0;
	float logFac = log2(widthFac); // 0 for width == 320, 1 for 640, 2 for 1280
	// I round the factor up with +0.5, so particles might be a bit too big (instead of a bit too small)
	// for resolutions between i*320 and (i+1)*320, like 800x600
	d_pix_shift = 7 - (int)(logFac + 0.5);
On the other hand, I'm not sure d_pix_shift is such a great idea at all, it's used like
pix = izi >> d_pix_shift;
Maybe it would be better to do a multiplication instead of a shift and use a corresponding factor?
like float d_pix_factor =  (float)r_refdef.vrect.width / 320.0f and then pix = (izi >> 7) * d_pix_factor;?
That way the particle sizes should scale better with resolutions (I haven't tested it though)

